Story time: My son bought a fixer upper house and with his full-time job, he’s been a bit overwhelmed with all that needs to get done. Like most people, his garage functions as so many things: storage, tools, lawn care, extra boxes, car port, workshop etc.  
I wanted to surprise him with a redone garage because sometimes getting your work space together is the first step to inspire you to tackle all the projects you’ve been avoiding. 
I always say: If a project feels too big, make the first step smaller. For most of you, that first step is to order your storage bins and racks and get a lot of the stuff into a good, uniform storage system. You can do that with The  Home Depot’s delivery within the App just like I did here. They have Same Day or Free Next Day Delivery on tons of items and it can save you a lot of time.  
Everything I used in this video will be linked. Should I show you how to build the tables? 
Love, Dad @The Home Depot

videos.text:
My garage workshop wasn’t chaos because I’m lazy.

It was chaos because I kept organizing for someone else’s brain, not mine.

So I stopped trying to “organize better” and started organizing differently…in a way that actually works with my ADHD.

Here are the 5 ADHD-friendly rules I gave myself:

1️⃣ What do I lose all the time? → Those get a designated, visual home (usually the pegboard)

2️⃣ Out of sight = out of mind. → If I can’t see it, I’ll forget I own it. Ditch the closed bins and cabinets for open bins and shelving

3️⃣ Drawers are for things I won’t forget→  Inwont wonder if I have a hammer 

4️⃣ Make it grab-and-go. → Tool bags packed by task so I don’t waste time gathering or putting things away.  I have one for caulking, electrical and plumbing.  Also ones for each power tool

5️⃣ Organize by activity, not item. → If it sticks stuff, it’s in the same bin. Taping? Gluing? Velcro-ing? Same category.  I don’t have time to organize every item and my brain thinks in terms of what I need to do

No perfect labels. No Pinterest bins. Just a system that actually works for the way my brain works.

✨ Tell me: which rule do you wish you’d tried sooner? 
Save these for later! 

#organizingtips #adhdwomen #garageworkshop #homemaintenance #doityourself

videos.text:
This parking garage collapse in New York City that happened only two years ago had shocked the city. It seems impossible with today’s technology to make such a critical engineering mistake but when assessments and assumptions aren’t made properly these failures will happen.

A previous survey and engineering assessment had the thought of a structural steel column encased in masonry that was supporting the structure. This was however not the case and as the deteriorated bricks were being removed and replaced the car park collapsed and caused massive damage. Even if this assumption was true of a steel column being there it would still have been ideal to shore the structure in order to verify that assumption/previous assessment. 

This collapse as ongoing trials in New York and has caused the department of buildings to crack down on future cases of negligence in New York City.
#engineering #construction #structuralengineering #civilengineering #truestory

videos.text:
Are you prepared to grab and go in the event of an emergency or natural disaster? According to a 2023 FEMA survey, half of Americans are not. Some have assembled disaster supplies (48%) or made a plan (37%), but the least common actions were planning with neighbors and getting involved in their community.

As a garage expert who has worked in hundreds of Northern California garages / homes, I can tell you at least 70% of the garages we’ve worked in DO NOT have an emergency supply section. Or if so, it’s minimal at best. Moving forward, this is a topic I will be recommending to our families.

The So Cal wildfires and other recent natural disasters serve as a reminder that one of our most important tasks this new year is ensuring your most important documents, memories and items are ready to go. In an instant. And that you’re prepared with food, water, first-aid and other necessities. 

Being prepared does not take a lot of time or effort...but IT DOES require your attention to get there.

Over the last couple days, I’ve been sharing how I’ve scanned and organized important papers and how you can do the same. I’ll continue sharing more on this topic as well as digitizing your photos and preparing supplies for an emergency. 

Meanwhile, one of our favorite weather-tight bin collections is 25% off. I’ve linked them on my LTK. They have super strong latches and a urethane foam seal to ensure your belongings remain safe from moisture, dust and pests. I like the file box which is a great bin for placing important papers, passports and more so you have something to grab and go.

You can see these bins in use in these projects.

I’m thinking of everyone in Southern California who has been affected and our first responders working round the clock. 

#emergencypreparedness #homeorganization #disasterpreparedness #love #simplyorganized #sohome

videos.text:
🔥 PSA: Most people are decluttering ALL wrong… and it’s why your house never actually stays organized. 🤯
I was working in a client’s home recently (not my own 👀), and this mistake showed up again and again:
👉 People buy all the pretty bins, labels, and baskets BEFORE they actually declutter.
Sure, it looks organized for a minute… but all you’ve really done is rearrange your clutter.
💡 The truth? If you’re organizing things you don’t even use (hello, expired spices and 3 can openers 😅), you’re wasting time, money, and energy.
Here’s the right order:
1️⃣ Empty the space
2️⃣ Be brutally honest + declutter what you don’t need
3️⃣ THEN organize what’s left
✨ When you declutter FIRST, your home stays organized for good — no more band-aid fixes with pretty containers.
Tough love? Yep. But this one shift will change your whole home. 💛
Would you agree with me, or are you team “buy the bins first”? Tell me in the comments ⬇️ and don’t forget to follow for more decluttering + home organization tips that actually LAST.

videos.text:
Replying to @queensharjack              Command Hooks are a type of hanging product made by 3M. To use them properly, follow these steps:

Choose the right size and type of Command Hook for your object or balloon garland and surface. Make sure the hook can hold the weight of your balloon garland and that the adhesive will adhere properly to the surface you want to use it on.
🎈 Clean the surface where you want to apply the hook. Wipe it down with a dry cloth to remove any dust, dirt, or oil.
🎈 Remove the backing from the hook and apply it to the surface. Press down firmly on the hook for 30 to 60 seconds to ensure a strong hold.
🎈 (optional) Wait at least one hour before hanging your balloon garland on the hook to allow the adhesive to set properly. 
(I personally do not wait an hr.) 
🎈 To remove the hook, gently pull the hook straight down to stretch the adhesive. Do not tug or pull at an angle, as this can cause the hook to break or come off in pieces.
🎈 To reuse the hook, remove any remaining adhesive from the hook and the surface using a dry cloth and a small amount of rubbing alcohol. Then follow the steps above to reapply the hook.
😃 I hope this helps!
